    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. You mentioned blockages or debris can cause false readings. What kind of things actually get in there? Is it mostly just ice, or are there other common things that pilots have to worry about clogging the tube?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ice is the primary culprit, especially during freezing rain or snow, but it's not the only thing that can clog a pitot tube. Debris like bird droppings, bugs, or even small pieces of hail can get sucked in and block the opening. Sometimes, even the pilot's own breath or condensation can cause issues if the system isn't properly vented.\n\nTo prevent these problems, pilots perform a specific test called a \"pitot heat check,\" where they turn on a heating element designed to melt any ice buildup. This is a critical safety step, often checked before takeoff and after landing, to ensure the airspeed indicator is giving accurate readings. If the needle doesn't move when the heat is applied, it indicates a blockage that needs immediate attention.\n\nIt's also worth noting that while a clogged pitot tube is dangerous, a completely frozen tube is a specific type of blockage that requires this heating procedure to resolve. Other forms of debris might require a physical inspection or cleaning by maintenance crew, depending on the severity. So, while ice is the most common issue, the pitot tube is vulnerable to a variety of external factors that pilots must constantly monitor.",
